TY  - JOUR
AB  - Paper presented at a Round Table Conference of the American Economic Association at New York City, December 27, 1935. The financing of an integrated social security program involves a decision as to the relative place in the total scheme of payroll and wage taxes as compared with other types of taxation. It is further necessary to decide whether certain taxes should be earmarked to provide all of the funds for specified types of benefits or whether the scope of each type of benefit should be determined by reference to other criteria than the yield of certain kinds of taxes. European experience shows the unwisdom of concentrating on one form of security regardless of the size of, and available methods of financing, the resulting residual problem. In deciding the appropriate part to be played by different types of taxes attention must be paid to: (a) the desired distribution of the burden between persons and generations, (b) the usefulness of the contributory principle as a method of defining eligibility for certain preferential benefits or as a device for promoting stabilization of employment, (c) the nature and distribution of the risk over time, and (d) the relative tax resources of the federal and local governments. The implications of these considerations are examined and the extent to which attention is paid to them in the Social Security act is analyzed.
