TY  - JOUR
AB  - The abandonment of the California plan of separation of state and local sources of tax revenue under an amendment adopted in 1933, after a generation of trial, naturally evokes an interesting query as to the results achieved under separation in this state. The present article attempts to summarize the effects of separation of sources in California and to compare them with those observed in other states. In general, marked similarity is observable to the experience of other states with separation. Full-value assessment of property failed of realization; a new equalization problem appeared in place of the former difficulty of equalization among counties; the anticipation of substantial benefits from a greater measure of home rule has not materialized, while at the same time this feature of the plan imparted a measure of inflexibility to the state tax system; a new problem was presented by the unequal losses to county tax rolls by the exemption of utility "operative" property from local taxes; local tax burdens were somewhat reduced under separation; finally, no marked tendency to extravagance is found in state or local expenditures as a result of the plan.
